<BaseLayout
  title="Teaching"
  description="Teaching in anthropology, ethnic studies, and Native American studies — courses, philosophy, and professional development."
>
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1>Teaching</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Courses in anthropology, ethnic studies, and Native American studies at a Hispanic-Serving Institution.</p>
  </div>

  <section>
    <h2>Courses</h2>
    <div class="card-grid">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Introduction to Ethnic Studies</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary">
          Cabrillo College (HSI, Santa Cruz, CA). Redesigned for the California Ethnic Studies
          mandate under conditions of rising fascism, student exhaustion, and institutional
          capture. The course operates through strike pedagogy — student self-organized,
          consensus-based, horizontal. Emergency flex weeks with three pathways: survival
          (check in, one point, glad you're alive), embodied knowledge (center self-care),
          or community-based work. No late penalties. Reading equivalencies that include
          embodied practice, elder interviews, community organizing, and zines.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Native American History &amp; Literature</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary">
          Cabrillo College. More direct structure than ethnic studies — the demographics
          are such that so many students are settlers, and there's an obligation to walk
          them through the history more directly as a way of keeping settler ideologies from
          recentering. Heavy emphasis on the California missions as precursors to fascist
          systems: totalitarian control enacted on Indigenous bodies, normalizing gender
          expression, movement, cultural expressions. Students learn to see current events
          not as a rupture but as a pattern.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Introduction to Cultural Anthropology</h3>
        <p class="text-secondary">
          Taught across multiple institutions: Agnes Scott College, College of Charleston,
          University of Virginia. Foundational course connecting four-field anthropology to
          contemporary questions of power, knowledge, and structural violence.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
    <p class="courses-note">
      Additional courses taught: Native American Studies, Archaeology, Visual Anthropology,
      Museum Studies, Cultural Resource Management, Historical Archaeology.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Teaching Philosophy</h2>
    <div class="card card--amber">
      <p>
        My work is about giving people language they need to imagine something different,
        and hopefully more freeing. I start with Module -1: community resources — local
        mutual aid, nonprofits, RoboBraille. Survival comes before learning.
      </p>
      <p>
        Students have a source library they can choose from — agency over what they engage with.
        Once per week they can substitute a reading with an equivalency: embodied practice,
        interviewing an elder, community organizing, life experience reflection. The idea is
        to let students actually <em>practice</em> ethnic studies and get credit for it.
        Zines count as readings — community knowledge.
      </p>
      <p>
        No late penalties, enabled by Autograder automation. I accept this may cause students
        to deprioritize my class relative to more rigid professors, but rigid deadlines are
        authoritarian pedagogy — habituating ourselves and our students into authoritarianism.
        The burnout pool model: any given week, individual students float in and out. Not
        everyone will do their readings all the time, but enough people will do them enough
        of the time to have good conversations. The goal: make the classroom survivable for
        everyone, including me.
      </p>
      <p>
        If ethnic studies can't help us adapt and build more resilient communities in the
        transition to a police state, we're probably not doing ethnic studies right.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Strike Pedagogy</h2>
    <div class="card card--amber">
      <p>
        I didn't adopt strike pedagogy — I developed it. I was barely holding on. I needed
        to fundamentally restructure how I did things, or I was going to quit the job. I shifted
        from planned curriculum to a consensus-based, student self-organized horizontal model.
      </p>
      <p>
        What happened was extremely pedagogically productive precisely because it was difficult.
        Students floundered. They had to struggle. They became frustrated. They really just
        didn't know what to do with their own power. I sat in the back. It decentered their
        relationship to me as the figure of authority at the center of the power structure.
        At one point, students literally had to look around the room and see who else was there.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because I was no longer responsible for making everything happen, I could observe.
        I am an anthropologist. I am a social scientist. This is what I do. Students who
        were quite skilled at doing the conceptual level were not able to do the practice.
        I told them that once they learn how to stop making themselves miserable, they'll
        have a lot of fun. And that was a mistake. I should never have told them that.
        I was right, but I should not have told them that, because they just got mad.
      </p>
      <p class="pub-refs">
        The framework honors the 1968&ndash;69 student strikes at SF State and UC Berkeley that
        created Ethnic Studies as a discipline. Documented in a 50-page pedagogical booklet
        and a zine: <em>ETHN-1 Is Now a Strike: Ethnic Studies in a Time of State Multiculturalism
        and a Neofascist Coup</em>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Professional Development</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Multiverse School</h3>
      <p>
        Continuing engagement with AI pedagogy and agentic development communities.
        Completed coursework in AI for Creatives. Ongoing participation in daily
        professional standup and collaborative learning. Upcoming: Agentic SDLC,
        Introduction to Agents.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Consulting</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Transformative Leadership Consulting</h3>
      <p>
        Independent equity and inclusion consulting through iChange Collaborative / Both And
        Partners (2016&ndash;present). Ongoing work running parallel to academic appointments,
        reflecting the same commitment to institutional transformation that drives the scholarly
        work and the tooling.
      </p>
      <p class="text-secondary" style="font-style: italic;">
        Details on scope and framing forthcoming.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
